quran[24]{c,v,t,f}:
55,17,"Lord of the two easts and of the two wests is He. {1}",footnotes:1:“The two Easts and the two Wests” may mean the two points of sunrise and the two points of sunset on the shortest day of winter and the longest day of summer as well as the easts and the wests of the two hemispheres of the earth. On the shortest day of winter the sun rises and sets making a small acute angle. On the contrary
55,18,"Which of the powers of your Lord {1} will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny?",footnotes:1:Here also
55,19,"He unleashed the two seas so that they merge together,"
55,20,"and yet there is a barrier between them which they may not overstep. {1}",footnotes:1:For explanation see( E. N. 68 of Surah Al-Furqan).
55,21,"Which of the wonders of your Lord will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny?"
55,22,"From these seas come forth pearls {1} and coral. {2}",footnotes:1:According to Ibn Abbas
55,23,"Which of the wonders of your Lord's power will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny? {1}",footnotes:1:Here also though the aspect of power in alaa is conspicuous
55,24,"His are the ships, {1} towering on the sea like mountains.",footnotes:1:His are the ships: Ships became possible only by His power. It is He Who blessed man with the capability and skill that he may build ships for crossing the oceans. It is He Who created on the earth the material from which ships could be built
55,25,"Which of the favours of your Lord will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny? {1}",footnotes:1:Here
55,26,"All {1} that is on earth will perish,",footnotes:1:From here to verse 30
55,27,"only the Person of your Lord, full of majesty and splendour, will endure."
55,28,"So which of the wonders of your Lord will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny? {1}",footnotes:1:Here
55,29,"All in the heavens and the earth entreat Him for their needs; a new, mighty task engages Him each day. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
55,30,"Which of your Lord's laudable attributes will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny? {1}",footnotes:1:Here
55,31,"O you twain, who are a burden (on the earth), {1} We shall attend to you and call you to account. {2}",footnotes:1:Thaqalan is derived from thiql which means a burden
55,32,"(We shall then see), which of the favours of your Lord will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny? {1}",footnotes:1:Here
55,33,"O company of jinn and men, if you have the power to go beyond the bounds of the heavens and the earth, go beyond them! Yet you will be unable to go beyond them for that requires infinite power. {1}",footnotes:1:The heavens and the earth: The universe or the kingdom of God. The verse means to impress this: It is not in your power to escape Allah’s grasp. When the time for the accountability of which you are being foretold comes
55,34,"Which of your Lord's powers will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny?"
55,35,"(If you so venture) a flame of fire and smoke {1} shall be lashed at you, which you shall be unable to withstand.",footnotes:1:The word shuwaz
55,36,"Which of your Lord's powers will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny?"
55,37,"(What will happen) when the heaven will be split asunder and will become crimson like leather? {1}",footnotes:1:This refers to the Day of Resurrection. Bursting of the heavens implies loosening of the discipline of the heavens
55,38,"Which of your Lord's powers will you twain – you men and jinn – then deny? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
55,39,"On that Day there will be no need to ask either men or jinn about their sins. {1}",footnotes:1:This is being explained by the subsequent sentence: The culprits there shall be recognized by their faces. It means that in that great assembly where all the former and the latter generations will have gathered together
